ce:section.ce:para:
The surface functions as well as elemental composition of each quantum dots sample was analyzed using XPS. Fig. 9
                         firstly shows the wide scans for the GQDs synthesized at 2 h, 4 h, 6 h and 8 h reaction times. The expected carbon (C1s) and oxygen (O1s) peaks are observed for all samples. The sodium (Na) peaks observed are probably due to excess NaOH used during synthesis. It is unclear where the silica peaks come from as there is no silica used in the starting materials. In order to obtain more details on the surface characteristics of these nanostructures and the types of bonds present, high resolution scans are obtained and deconvoluted to determine the types of bonds present within the structure of the QDs. For the GQDs (Fig. 9), the C1s spectra were deconvoluted in order to confirm the type of C-bonds present as well as to prove the presence of the –COOH groups (Table 5A
                        ). At all synthetic times, three peaks were observed at binding energies of 294 eV, 292 eV and 290 eV corresponding to C=C/C-C which are the sp2 carbons, CO which are the sp3 carbons and CO, respectively. The CO and CO peaks also confirm the presence of –COOH groups.
